    <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
        <body>
            <div xml:id="KT372-kilavi">
                <p type="edition">iravukkuṟi vantoḻukāniṉṟa talaimakaṉ kēṭpat tōḻi talaimakaṭkuc
                    colluvāḷāyc colliyatu. </p>


                <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">Uttered by the confidante, as one who speaks to
                    HER, for HIM to hear, who stood there motionless, having come to the night
                    tryst. </p>
            </div>

            <div xml:id="KT372">
                <lg type="edition">
                    <l> paṉaittalaik karukkuṭai neṭumaṭal kuruttoṭu māyak</l>
                    <l> kaṭuvaḷi tokutta neṭuveṇ kuppaik</l>
                    <l> kaṇaṅkoḷ cimaiya vaṇaṅkuṅ kāṉa</l>
                    <l> lāḻitalai vīciya vayirccēṟ ṟaruvik</l>
                    <l> kūḻaipe yekkark kuḻīiya patukkai</l>
                    <l> pularpataṅ koḷḷā vaḷavai</l>
                    <l> yalareḻun taṉṟiv vaḻunka lūrē.</l>


                </lg>

                <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                    <l rend="indent"> Before the mounds accumulated in the dunes</l>
                    <l rend="indent"> reached dry consistency, to be poured on the hair <note place="foot">The sense here is fairly dubious. Cām. takes  <term xml:lang="ta">kūḻai </term> as "woman's hair" (for which there are clear parallels such as NA 23.2, 368.5) and  <term xml:lang="ta">patukkai</term> as "mud" to be applied to that hair, similar to the passage in KT 113. But if something like this is meant, it is expressed in a fairly elliptical way.  </note>        ,
                </l>
                <l rend="indent2"> from the river mouth  <note place="foot">What is <term xml:lang="ta"> aruvi</term> supposed to be here? There is an extra entry in the DEDR 225 giving "river mouth" as a meaning of <term xml:lang="ta">  aruvi </term>. Can this be the point – a mixture of the different kinds of soil coming together where the river mounds into the sea?  </note>      with mud [and] fine sand flung</l>
            <l rend="indent9"> by the sea’s [wave] heads <note place="foot">
                <term xml:lang="ta"> āḻi-talai</term>, "sea heads" might be seen as a metaphor for "wave", instead of taking talai as an expletive. </note>    ,
        </l>
        <l rend="indent3"> in the seashore grove, where the peaks in groups are yielding <note place="foot"> Is this supposed to mean that the heaps of sand already there (= <term xml:lang="ta"> cimaiyam </term>) are oppressed by the newly accumulating sands (= <term xml:lang="ta"> kuppai </term>)? Cām. even reads <term xml:lang="ta"> aṇaṅku,</term> "to torment", here, while the sandhi allows also for a more neutral <term xml:lang="ta"> vaṇaṅku,</term> "to bow".    </note>
    </l>
    <l rend="indent3"> to the long white heaps piled up by the fierce wind,</l>
    <l rend="indent4"> so that with the sprouts the saw-edged long stems</l>
    <l rend="indent6"> disappear up to the top of the Palmyras, <note place="foot">The construction and impact of lines 1-6 are insufficiently marked and quite unclear, apart from the topos of the Palmyras being buried by sand (cf. KT 248). </note>
    </l>
    <l> gossip arose in this noisy village.</l>


</lg>
</div>
